text=>>comment%3c%3c%0aSummary: Indicating the current time of a post using the file's mtime.%0aParent: (Technology.)Jekyll%0aIncludeMe: [[(Technology.)Jekyll]]%0aCategories: [[!HowTos]]%0aTags: jekyll, mtime%0a(:tags-hide jekyll, mtime:)%0aSource: http://jekyll.alphavice.com/destination/jekyll/2013/09/20/leveraging-filesystem-mtime-within-jekyll.html%0aPosted: Fri Sep 27 10:16:35 2013%0a>>%3c%3c%0a[[#excerpt]]%0a[[Jekyll]] posts include the publication date in their file name, and%0aare published under that in the destination folder. By default, the%0adate is taken from the file name, or from the @@date:@@ field in the%0apost's front matter.%0a%0aHowever, sometimes you'll want to edit a post, updating some info,%0acorrecting a broken link, adding something new from comments, etc. In%0athis case, you might want to also indicate the current version of the%0afile.%0a[[#excerptend]]%0a%0aThis could be done a few ways. This particular way will use the file's%0amodification time (mtime).%0a%0aIn this case, we'll be using a [[Liquid]] filter, which lets us do the%0afollowing in our site files:%0a%0a(:source lang=html5  tabwidth=2  :)%0a%3cul>%0a  %3cli class="meta">Published on: {{ page.date }}%3c/li>%0a  %3cli class="meta">Last modified on: {{ page.path | file_date | date_to_rfc822 }}%3c/li>%0a%3c/ul>%0a(:sourceend:)%0a%0a!! Plugin%0a%0aCreate a file to hold the plugin code in the @@_plugins@@ directory of%0ayour source directory (creating it if necessary). Add the following to%0athat file:%0a%0a(:source lang=ruby linenum tabwidth=2 header="_plugins/file_date.rb" :)%0amodule Jekyll%0a  module MyFilters%0a    def file_date(input)%0a      File.mtime(input)%0a    end%0a  end%0aend%0a%0a# this is necessary to tell Jekyll to use the filter.%0aLiquid::Template.register_filter(Jekyll::MyFilters)%0a(:sourceend:)%0a
